SIMPLE: foolery
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Foolery
<hw>Fool"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Fooleries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The practice
of folly; the behavior of a fool; foolish behavior; absurdity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Folly in fools bears not so strong a note,⟦br⟧
As <qex>foolery</qex> in the wise, when wit doth dote.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An act of folly or weakness; a foolish practice;
something absurd or nonsensical.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That Pythagoras, Plato, or Orpheus, believed in any of these
<qex>fooleries</qex>, it can not be suspected.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foolfish</ent>⟦br⟧
